In order to account for 'POODLE' CVE (http://www.cve.mitre.org/cgi-bin/cvename.cgi?name=CVE-2014-3566), Tomcat needs this setting applied to its secure connector.

Here is the article that describes the settings -> http://wiki.apache.org/tomcat/Security/POODLE

You can use either `null` for backward compatibility, or create a **secure** default of `"TLSv1.2,TLSv1.1,TLSv1,SSLv2Hello"`.

Unfortunately, the property itself is defined on the protocol handler endpoint, which is not publicly accessible through `Connector` and `AbstractHttp11JsseProtocol` objects, however Tomcat's `AbstractProtocol` object supports `setProperty` method, that delegates to the endpoint by reflection, and can be used to apply this particular setting, e.g:

``` java
class TomcatEmbeddedServletContainerFactory

protected void configureSsl(AbstractHttp11JsseProtocol<?> protocol, Ssl ssl) {
  ...
  String sslEnabledProtocols = ssl.getSslEnabledProtocols( );
  if (sslEnabledProtocols != null) {
    // sslEnabledProperty itself is defined on the 'endpoint' object of the 
    // 'AbstractHttp11JsseProtocol'.
    // There is no public getter for the 'endpoint', but protocol's 'setProperty' will 
    // properly delegate setting of this value to the endpoint through reflection
    protocol.setProperty( "sslEnabledProtocols", sslEnabledProtocols  );
  }
  ...
}

```

